The metal-organic frameworks (MOFs) and modified zeolites have been introduced for the hydrogenation of EAQ. The ordered structure, higher surface area, and constant distribution of pore size of the zeolites (e.g., MCM-41 and SBA-15) make them better to support Pd nanoparticles and reduce the diffusion resistance. It enhances the surface for systematic dispersion of metal in the three-phase catalytic reactor (Beck et al. 1992; Kresge et al. 1992; Tanev and Pinnavaia, 1996). Guo et al. (2017) determined the pore diameter of zeolites (MCM-22 and Beta) and the effect on the EAQ hydrogenation. It was found that the monolithic catalyst (0.8% Pd/MCM-41/COR) demonstrated the highest yield of H2O2 (7.54 g L−1) and selectivity (85.3%) in the production of H2O2 by AQ process. The efficiency of 0.8% Pd/MCM-41/COR monolithic catalyst (1573 gH2O2gPd-1h-1\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
